75 (i) Where the monthly income of an applicant or recipient for PACE is in excess of the
76 exemptions allowed, the applicant or recipient, if otherwise eligible for PACE under this chapter
77 shall be liable to pay to the provider of medical care or service an amount which shall be equal to
78 the excess income reduced by the difference between the applicable MassHealth deductible-
79 income standard and 300 percent of the federal benefit rate.
80 (j) PACE recipients who are eligible for the “special income eligibility group,”,
81 established under 42 CFR 435.217 and pursuant to federal regulations at 42 CFR 435.726 and 42
82 CFR 460.184, shall not be liable to pay to the provider of medical care or service an amount
83 which shall be equal to the excess income reduced by the difference between the applicable
84 MassHealth deductible-income standard and 300 percent of the federal benefit rate in order to
85 remain enrolled in PACE.
86 (k) Any applicant for or recipient of PACE, or the legal representative of such applicant
87 or recipient, aggrieved by the failure of MassHealth to grant medical assistance shall have the
88 opportunity to appeal said decision in accordance with section 47 of this chapter.
89 (l) To the extent authorized by federal law, MassHealth is hereby authorized to grant
90 presumptive eligibility for up to 90 days to applicants applying for enrollment in PACE.
91 Individuals who are enrolled in MassHealth standard shall be deemed presumptively eligible for
92 PACE if they meet the clinical assessment criteria.
93 (m) MassHealth shall use dual capitation agreements with Medicare and Medicaid, as
94 described under 42 CFR 460, for payment for Medicaid and Medicare services in which PACE
95 programs (or organizations?) shall be at full or partial financial risk for any services that they
96 authorize and purchase on behalf of an enrollee. Capitation rates shall be adequate to ensure the
